#### 1. About/Overview

â€‹    Based on project 3 and 4, this project aims to add an option for user to play GUI adventure game by implementing the view and updating controller for the whole MVC peoject.

The GUI include:

- Give user an option to make game settings on a JMenu.
- Give user an option to restart game using exactly the same dungeon as before on a JMenu.
- Display the dungeon to screen, only the revealed locations will be shown to screen.
- Allow player to move through dungeon using mouse click or keyboard arrow keys.
- Display the details of player's current location information.
- Give user an option to get the player's description.
- Give user an option to pick up treasure or arrows using keyboard.
- Give user an option to shoot an arrow by using keyboard.
- Provide clear indication of the results of each action the player takes.

#### 2. List of features

Notes: classes in other packages are same as they are in project 4.

##### Package dungeon

###### (1) ReadonlyDungeonModel

- getStartPosition(): Get start cave position in the dungeon.
- getEndPosition(): Get end cave position in the dungeon.

+ getPlayer(): Get player in the dungeon.
+ getSmellLevel(): Get smell level from player's current location.
+ getPlayerDescription(): Get the description of player.
+ getLocationDescription(): Get the current location description of player.
+ getLocations(): Get locations in dungeon.
+ getDungeon(): Get every location description in dungeon.
+ isGameOver(): Return the game status.
  - Return true if game is over;
  - Return false otherwise.
###### (2) Dungeon 

Entends **ReadonlyDungeonModel** Interface

+ Move(int direction): Move the player in the dungeon.Throws *IllegalArgumentException* if direction is not in the range of [1,4] or unavailable move at current location. 
  - direction 1: north
  - direction 2: south
  - direction 3: east
  - direction 4: west
+ shoot(int direction, int distance): Shoot the arrow in the dungeon.Throws *IllegalArgumentException* if direction or distance is not in the range of [1,4]. 
  - direction 1: north
  - direction 2: south
  - direction 3: east
  - direction 4: west
+ pickArrow(): Player picks arrow at current location. 
+ pickTreasure(): Player picks treasure at current location. 
+ combat(): Player combats with monster.  
  - Return 0 if there's no monster at player's current location;
  - Return 1 if player is eaten by monster;
  - Return 2 if player is able to eascape from an injured monster.
+ resetPlayer(): Reset player for new game, including position, arrows and treasure.
+ resetStartCave(): Reset start cave position for new game.
+ resetEndCave(): Reset end cave position for new game.
+ resetDungeon(): Reset dungeon for new game.

###### (3) DungeonModel

Implement **Dungeon** Interface

+ Dungeon(int x, int y, boolean wrapping, int interconnectivity, int percentage, int monsterAmount): Create a Dungeon object using given parameters with size = x * y .

  Throws *IllegalArgumentException* when

  - x < 5 || y < 5
  - Interconnectivity < 0
  - Percentage < 20 || percentage > 100
  - monsterAmount < 1 || monsterAmount > cave number
  - interconnectivity > x * y + 1 if wrapping == true
  - interconnectivity > x * y + x + y + 1 if wrapping == false

  Throws *IllegalArgumentException* when

  - There's no path with length longer than 4 between start cave and end cave.

###### (4) DungeonController(for text-based game)

+ playerGame(Dungeon m): Execute a single game of dungeon given a dungeon Model, when game is over, the playerGame method ends. Throws *IllegalArgumentException* when model is null.

###### (5) DungeonConsoleController

Implement **DungeonController** Interface

+ DungeonConsoleController(Readable in, Appendable out): Create a controller object. Throws *IllegalArgumentException* if in or out is null.

###### (6) DungeonViewController(for GUI game)

- playerGame(Dungeon m): Execute a single game of dungeon given a dungeon Model. Throws *IllegalArgumentException* when model is null.
- handlePanelClick(int direction): Handle an action in a single label of the panel, such as to make a move.

###### (7) DungeonViewControllerImpl

Implement **DungeonViewController, ActionListener and Keylistener** Interface

- DungeonViewControllerImpl(Dungeon model, DungeonView view): Create a controller object. Throws *IllegalArgumentException* if model or view is null.
- actionPerforemed(): Override this method to catch button click events and react to them.
- keyPressed(): Override this method to catch key pressed events and react to them.
- keyReleased(): Override this method to catch key released events and react to them.

###### (8) DungeonView

- refresh(): Refresh the view to reflect any changes in the game state.
- makeVisible(): Make the view visible to start the game session.
- setListeners(ActionListener clicks, KeyListener keys): Set action listener and key listeners to components on frame.
- resetFocus(): Set focus back to main fram so that keyboard events work.
- setOperationDescription(String result): Set operation result for view to draw.
- setInformation(String info): Set information of player for view to draw.
- addDungeon(Location location, int x, int y): Add visited dungeon for view to draw.
- updateDungeon(): Update dungeon locations for view to draw.
- addClickListener(DungeonViewController listener): Set up the controller to handle click events in this view.
- createSettings(): Pop up setting dialog and return the user input.
- restartGame(): Restart game.

###### (9) DungeonSwingView

Implement **DungeonView** Interface

- DungeonSwingView(ReadonlyDungeonModel model):  Create a view object. Throws *IllegalArgumentException* if model is null.

###### (10) DungeonPanel

- DungeonPanel(ReadonlyDungeonModel model):  Create a DungeonPanel object, throws *IllegalArgumentException* if model is null.
- paintComponent(Graphics g): Paint the component.
- addNewLocation(Location location, int x, int y): Add new visited locations to panel.
- updateVisitedLocation(): Update player's visited locations.
- resetPanel(): Reset panel display when new game starts.

###### (11) ButtonPanel

- ButtonPanel():  Create a ButtonPanel object.
- paintComponent(Graphics g): Paint the component.
- addActionListener(ActionListener clicks): Set action listener to information button on the panel.
- updateDescription(): Update player's description.

###### (12) DescriptionPanel

- DescriptionPanel():  Create a DescriptionPanel object.
- paintComponent(Graphics g): Paint the component.
- updateOpResult(): Update operation result for this panel to draw.

###### (13) SettingsDialog

- SettingsDialog():  Create a SettingsDialog object.
- getTextValue(): Return text value.

#### 3. How to Run

Use "java -jar Dungeon.jar" to run the main method. Then the program will ask "Please enter game type you want to play:" 

- input "text" for text-based game.
- input "gui" for GUI game.

(1) if user input "text", the program will run text-based game

This text-based project need six parameters in order to create the dungeon:

+ x(row size for dungeon), must be greater than 4;
+ y(column size for dungeon), must be greater than 4;
+ type of dungeon: "true" for wrapping dungeon while "false" for non-wrapping dungeon;
+ Interconnectivity, can't be negative number, and can't be greater than the max interconnectivity of a dungeon with size x*y;
+ treasure and arrow percentage, must be within the range[20,100];
+ monster amount, must be positive number and can't be greater than the max capacity of a dungeon with size x*y.

For example, input "5 5 false 0 100 1" to create a non-wrapping dungeon with size 5 * 5, 100% of caves contains treasure, and 100% locations(caves and tunnels) contains arrows, finally add 1 monster to the dungeon. After creating the dungeon, user is able to interact with the program based on the information and instructions given by the program.

(2) if user input "gui", the program will run GUI game.

#### 4. How to Use the Program

(1) For text-based game, input "text" to run text-based game, then:

- Create a dungeon by input something like "5 5 false 0 100 1".
- Input "P" to make an pick operation, then input "arrow" or "treasure" to pick different kind of products.
- Input "M" to make an move operation, then input "north", "south", "east" or "west" to select a movement direction.
- Input "S" to make an shoot operation, then input "north", "south", "east" or "west" to select a shooting direction, finally input a valid number(range[1-4]) to make a shoot operation.
- Quit the game whenever user input "q".

(2) For GUI game, input "gui" to run GUI game, then:

- The program will create a default dungeon with parameters "7 7 true 15 50 2".

- User is able to use the arrow keyboard to move through dungeon.

- User is also able to click the nearby location to move through dungeon. (Only by clicking the location with exactly 1 distance considered a valid click, invalid click will not advance the player.)

- User is able to press key "Q" to pick arrows at current location.

- User is able to press key "E" to pick treasure at current location.

- User is able to press key "R", continuing with a direction key "W" for north, "S" for south, "A" for west and "D" for east. Then a frame will pop up, user then need to select a shooting distance and click "OK" button to make a shoot operation. For example: press R, then press S, then select 1 and click OK will shoot south with 1 distance. Close the dialog or click cancel will cancel this shooting operation.

  ![avatar][shooting dialog]

- User is able to click Settings to make settings and click start button to start a new game.
- User is able to click Restart to restart the game with everything same as last game.
- User is able to click Quit to quit the game.

![avatar][menu]

- User is able to click Information button on the left of the screen in order to see the player's information.

#### 5. Design/Model Changes

Compared to project 4, in order to implement restart game, add 4 public methods in Dungeon:

- resetPlayer(): Reset player for new game, including position, arrows and treasure.
- resetStartCave(): Reset start cave position for new game.
- resetEndCave(): Reset end cave position for new game.
- resetDungeon(): Reset dungeon for new game.

Compared to original design in project 5, changes are as follows:

- Add a ReadonlyDungeonModel interface, which only has get method, for view to use.
- Originally, the SettingsDialog object is created when controller catch the button click event. However, controller should call view to create the SettingsDialog object, therefore, add createSettings() method in view to create SettingsDialog object instead of giving controller the authority.

#### 6. Assumptions

- When program runs, it will ask user to choose the game mode(text-based or GUI), then according to user's selection, run the corresponding mode.
- If user want to use mouse click to control the move of player, the valid click area is one locations around player's current location(north, south, west and east). Other invalid click area will not advance the player.
- Restart menu will reset everything the same as last game.

+ One cave can only hold one Otyugh.
+ If player enter a cave with a injured monster, player has 50% possibility not being eaten by Otyugh, therefore, the player is able to make a next operation at current location; however, if player don't move to another location nearby, after the player's operation, the Otyugh will try to eat player again.
+ If Otyugh is slayed by player, it will vanish (no body or smell will be detected).
+ If player choose to pick arrow at current location, the player will pick all arrows, not just part of them.
+ If arrows at one location was picked by player, it will no longer generate again at that location.

#### 7. Limitations

+ Since the DungeonViewControllerImpl implements DungeonViewController, ActionListener and KeyListener, it is difficult to test the controller, since we cannot mock the events such as keyPressed or mouseClicked or buttonClicked.
+ When user want to create a dungeon but given invalid parameters, the program will throw exceptions, both in text-based game and GUI game.
+ When the dungeon is created with big size, the game running speed will become slow, which I believe is caused by the inefficient of my code to refresh the dungeon state in view.
+ As the dungeon is randomly created, I'm not sure which size of dungeon will ensure the start and end position with path length beyond 4 can always be found. In this project, I limit the size of dungeon to at least 5*5. But if this dungeon can't find a start cave and end cave with path length beyond 4, the program will throw an IllegalArgumentException.
